# UI Kit source of truth

The UI Kit is the visual source of truth for this project.

The source of truth is composed of:
1. `src/pages/ComponentsPage.tsx` as the reference showcase.
2. `src/components/ui/*` as the primitive implementation layer.
3. `src/index.css` theme tokens as the color / typography / radius foundation.

Application screens must conform to the UI Kit. The UI Kit must not be silently changed to match ad hoc screen changes.

## Protected files

Do not modify these files unless the user explicitly asks for a UI Kit change:

- `src/pages/ComponentsPage.tsx`
- `src/components/ui/*`
- `src/index.css` theme tokens

If one of these files appears inconsistent with the app, stop and report the gap before editing.

## ComponentsPage policy

- Treat `src/pages/ComponentsPage.tsx` as a protected reference, not as a living mirror of the app.
- Do not update ComponentsPage simply because the app has diverged.
- If ComponentsPage changed unexpectedly, identify the commit and propose a targeted revert.
- The app should converge back to ComponentsPage and `ui/*`, not the other way around.

## UI compliance rules

Before changing UI, check:

1. Is there an existing primitive in `src/components/ui/*`?
2. Is the visual pattern shown in `src/pages/ComponentsPage.tsx`?
3. Is there already a shared pattern in `src/components/shared/*`?
4. Would the change create a local visual fork?

Prefer existing UI primitives over local markup.

Do not introduce one-off styles for:

- badges
- chips
- pills
- buttons
- tabs
- inputs
- tables
- cards
- empty states
- avatars
- section headers

## Forbidden without explicit approval

- modifying `ComponentsPage.tsx`
- changing variants or base styles in `src/components/ui/*`
- changing global theme tokens in `src/index.css`
- creating a new design-system layer
- adding local badge / chip / pill styles
- using arbitrary hex colors in product UI
- replacing UI primitives with custom markup
- adapting the UI Kit to match a local screen change

## If a local UI diverges from the kit

First determine whether the divergence is caused by:

- a corrupted / modified UI Kit file,
- a local screen implementation bypassing the kit,
- a missing primitive or missing documented variant,
- a product pattern that is intentionally outside the primitive kit.

Then recommend one of:

- revert the UI Kit file,
- migrate the app back to existing primitives,
- request explicit approval for a UI Kit evolution,
- document the pattern as intentionally out of kit.

## Audit requirements

When auditing UI compliance, report:

- UI Kit files modified since the reference commit,
- app components diverging from ComponentsPage,
- local forks of primitives,
- hardcoded colors and arbitrary spacing,
- rogue variants,
- duplicated avatar / badge / tab / empty-state patterns,
- whether the fix should revert the kit or update the app.

## Implementation rules

When fixing UI compliance:

- keep changes incremental,
- prefer app-side fixes over kit changes,
- do not touch business logic,
- do not touch lifecycle, validation, YAML export, publish flow, or data models,
- do not refactor large containers unless the divergence is structural,
- run `npm test` and `npm run build` after changes.